EDS Processing Part 2: Signal Extraction from the (denoised) Datacube¶

Author: Lukas Grünewald
Last edited: 25.10.23
HyperSpy Version: 1.7.5

Purpose:¶

Qualitative elemental maps (background-corrected peak net-intensities) are extracted from the (denoised) EDS dataset.

Usage:¶

Copy this notebook in the same folder containing the Part1-MSA notebook and the .bcf file.
Run the accompanying Part1-MSA notebook beforehand to perform pre-processing and, e.g., PCA denoising.

Define helper functions¶

In [5]:
def create_folder(folderpath):
    """
    Create a folder.

    Parameters
    ----------
    folderpath : Path and name of folder. 
    """
    try: os.mkdir(folderpath)
    except OSError: print(f'Creation of the directory {folderpath} failed. Probably already present.')
    else: print(f'Successfully created the directory {folderpath}')
    
def save_scaled_tiff(s, filename):
    """
    Save 2D HyperSpy signal as 32-bit scaled tiff for ImageJ/Fiji.
    The scale and unit is taken from the axis_manager of s. 
    Make sure s.axes_manager.scale and s.axes_manager.units are correct.

    Parameters
    ----------
    s : 2D HyperSpy signal
    filename : path/to/output.tif
    """
    # Create temporary copy of s
    s2 = s.deepcopy()
    s2.change_dtype('float32') # from float64
    
    # Failsave for tiff scale: µ cannot be set, use u instead
    unit = s2.axes_manager[-1].units
    if s2.axes_manager[-1].units== 'µm':
        unit = 'um'
        
    # Save file
    imwrite(filename, s2.data, 
            imagej=True, 
            resolution=(1./s.axes_manager[-1].scale, 1./s.axes_manager[-1].scale), 
            metadata={'unit': unit})
    
    # Clean up
    del s2

Extract elemental maps¶

We can extract x-ray peak intensities, by using one or more of the following options:

  • Option 1 --> Quick extraction of selected (isolated) peaks. Good place to start and understand options 1-4.
  • Option 2 --> Same as option 1, but parameters are loaded from a file from a previous analysis.
  • Option 3 --> Extract multiple (isolated) peaks at once, good for repeated analysis of the same elements
  • Option 4 --> Same as option 3, but parameters are loaded from a file from a previous analysis.
  • Option 5 --> Model fitting for overlapping peaks

Option 1: Set up and extract single x-ray lines¶

Extract a single x-ray line intensity by integration in a specific energy window. The following cells can be run multiple times for different x-ray lines.

The background is modeled by a straight line, whose two defining points are the average values from two background windows placed left and right from the peak. The intensity/counts inside the integration window are added for each pixel. For each x-ray line adjust the parameters:

  • xray_line -> Name of element and x-ray line
  • bwl -> position of "background window left" x FWHM at x-ray line energy
  • bwr -> position of "background window right" x FWHM at x-ray line energy
  • bww -> width of background windows x FWHM at x-ray line energy
  • iww -> width of integration window x FWHM at x-ray line energy

Run the cells below for each element of interest. If there is a peak overlap, you can also do a model fit with Option 3.

In [9]:
# User Input
xray_line = 'Sr_Ka'

bwl = 1.5    # position of left background window (bwl*130eV from Mn_Ka Energy resolution)
bwr = 1.5    # position of right background window (bwr*130eV from Mn_Ka Energy resolution)
bww = 1.0    # width of background windows (bww*130eV from Mn_Ka Energy resolution)
iww = 1.2    # Default is 2.0 (times FWHM), however in literature 1.2*FWHM is often used as a balance of peak/background ratio
In [10]:
# Set up and plot x-ray line + background window position. Inspect with zoom-funtion in UI.
s.set_elements([]) # Clear present element list
s.set_lines([xray_line])

# Make a copy of the summed spectrum
s1 = s.sum().deepcopy()

bw_pos = s1.estimate_background_windows(line_width=[bwl, bwr], windows_width=bww)
iw_pos = s1.estimate_integration_windows(windows_width=iww)

print('Background window position:\n',  xray_line, '\t', bw_pos[0])
print('Integration window position:\n',  xray_line, '\t', iw_pos[0])

Option 3: Multiple x-ray lines¶

The same is done as in option 1 and 2.
However, all background windows (and even integration window) positions are defined for each x-ray line before extracting the background-subtracted intensities.
To start, we specify integration window width (iww) and X-ray lines of interest:

In [30]:
# User input
iww = 1.2 # Default is 2.0(*FWHM)
xray_lines = ['Er_La', 'O_Ka', 'Y_Ka', 'Ba_La', 'Cu_Ka', 'Ti_Ka']
xray_lines = sorted(xray_lines)

    roi_bwl[i].interactive(s_tmp, color='tab:blue')
    roi_bwr[i].interactive(s_tmp, color='tab:orange')

In [39]:
for i, line in enumerate(xray_lines):
    # Save window setup as an image
    s_tmp = s2.isig[bw_pos[i][0]-buffer:bw_pos[i][3]+buffer]
    s_tmp.plot(xray_lines=[line], background_windows=[bw_pos[i,:]], integration_windows=[iw_pos[i]])
    fig, ax = plt.gcf(), plt.gca()
    ax.set_title(f'{line} Integration Setup', fontsize='large')
    fig.tight_layout(pad=0.5)
    fig.savefig(info_path / (line + '.png'), dpi=300)
    fig.savefig(info_path / (line + '.svg'))
    plt.close()
    
    # Save signal
    s2.save(info_path / (line + '.hspy'), overwrite=True)

    # Save background/integration window parameters
    f = open(info_path / (line + '_parameters.txt'), 'w')
    f.write(f'# X-ray line: {line}\n')
    f.write(f'# Background window position ({s2.axes_manager[-1].units}, rows 0-3) and Integration window position ({s2.axes_manager[-1].units}, rows 4-5)\n')
    np.savetxt(f, bw_pos[i,:], delimiter='\n')
    np.savetxt(f, np.array(iw_pos[i]).reshape((2,)))
    f.close()

Option 5: Fit Gaussians to seperate overlapping lines¶

In case of x-ray peak overlap, we can try to fit Gaussians to model the x-ray lines (actually, the whole x-ray line family).
Here, we use it to separate the overlapping Ba L$\alpha$ and Ti K$\alpha$ lines as an example.

The procedure is as follows:

  1. Crop the energy dimension to the peak-overlap region (the less Gaussian to fit, the faster). You may include a few surrounding peaks if there is possible overlap with multiple lines (especially at energies < 5 keV).
  2. Add possible elements of the sample and signals from spurious x-rays from the microscope hardware, contamination. Based on the energy intervall, HyperSpy will add only the relevant x-ray transitions in the selected energy interval.
  3. Initialize a HyperSpy model. Relevant x-ray lines in the energy region will be added automatically as Gaussian functions with fixed position and width.
  4. Optional: Re-calibrate energy axis if peak positions or peak widths appear wrong.
  5. Add a background function to the model: For TEM, a linear funtion (polynomial of 1st order) is OK. For SEM you may want to try the default 6th order polynomial.
  6. Specifiy some optional model parameters: Add extra X-ray lines, change fitting bounds, ...
  7. Fit the model at a specific location, e.g. at position (0,0), to initialize some sensible starting parameters.
  8. Run multifit to fit at each pixel. This may take a while.

Approximate duration of the multifit on the SI.
For qt backend: Close window with fitted curve, it will skew duration estimation since it updates for every fit.

In [74]:
# For qt backend, we close all open windows
#plt.close('all')
In [75]:
def approx_multifit_duration(model, n_inav = 20):
    fit_timings = []
    for i in range(n_inav):
        p0 = np.round(np.random.random()*model.axes_manager.navigation_shape[0])
        p1 = np.round(np.random.random()*model.axes_manager.navigation_shape[1])
        model.axes_manager.indices = (p0, p1)
        t = %timeit -r 1 -n 1 -o -q model.fit(bounded=True, return_info=False)
        fit_timings.append(t.timings[0])
    tot_duration = np.average(fit_timings)*model.axes_manager.navigation_shape[0]*model.axes_manager.navigation_shape[1] #in seconds    
    print(f'Fit on a single position takes approximately {np.round(np.average(fit_timings)*1e3, 3)} ms. (Average of {n_inav} positions)')
    print(f'Multifit of {model.axes_manager.navigation_shape[0]}*{model.axes_manager.navigation_shape[1]}={model.axes_manager.navigation_shape[0]*model.axes_manager.navigation_shape[1]} pixels will take approximately {np.round(tot_duration)} s (or {np.round(tot_duration/60, 2)} min, {np.round(tot_duration/3600, 2)} h)')
In [76]:
approx_multifit_duration(m)

Fit on a single position takes approximately 74.935 ms. (Average of 20 positions)
Multifit of 65*45=2925 pixels will take approximately 219.0 s (or 3.65 min, 0.06 h)
